{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657930"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:39:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:39:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20692"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20692"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.35,0.61,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13568"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95600"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13568"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78410"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"5340"},{"type":"tags","id":"11657"},{"type":"tags","id":"12452"},{"type":"tags","id":"12570"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32553"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95600"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman is found unconscious in her garage with a running car engine. She has cherry-red skin, oxygen saturation of 98% on pulse oximetry, and a carboxyhaemoglobin level of 45%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains the complex pathophysiological mechanisms contributing to tissue hypoxia in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Competitive inhibition of cytochrome c oxidase in mitochondria","Formation of methaemoglobin with impaired oxygen binding","Left shift of the oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve","Destruction of alveolar-capillary membrane integrity","Direct vasodilation of cerebral blood vessels"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is suffering from carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning. While CO has multiple pathophysiological effects, the most significant mechanism contributing to tissue hypoxia is the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft shift of the oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve\u003C/strong\u003E. When CO binds to haemoglobin (with approximately 250-fold greater affinity than oxygen), it not only reduces oxygen-carrying capacity but also increases the affinity of the remaining haeme groups for oxygen. This left-shifted dissociation curve means that haemoglobin holds onto oxygen more tightly and releases less oxygen to tissues, exacerbating tissue hypoxia beyond what would be expected from the reduced oxygen-carrying capacity alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitive inhibition of cytochrome c oxidase in mitochondria\u003C/strong\u003E - While CO can inhibit cytochrome c oxidase at high concentrations, this is a secondary mechanism and less significant than its effects on haemoglobin and the oxygen dissociation curve. This mechanism becomes more relevant in severe poisoning.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of methaemoglobin with impaired oxygen binding\u003C/strong\u003E - Methaemoglobinaemia occurs when the iron in haemoglobin is oxidised from the ferrous (Fe\u00b2\u207a) to the ferric (Fe\u00b3\u207a) state, which is caused by oxidising agents like nitrites, not by carbon monoxide. CO forms carboxyhaemoglobin, not methaemoglobin.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDestruction of alveolar-capillary membrane integrity\u003C/strong\u003E - CO does not damage the alveolar-capillary membrane. The patient\u0027s normal PaO\u2082 indicates intact gas exchange at the alveolar level.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect vasodilation of cerebral blood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - While CO can cause cerebral vasodilation, this is a compensatory response to hypoxia rather than a primary mechanism causing tissue hypoxia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s normal oxygen saturation on pulse oximetry (98%) despite severe hypoxia demonstrates an important limitation of standard pulse oximeters, which cannot distinguish between oxyhaemoglobin and carboxyhaemoglobin. The carboxyhaemoglobin level of 45% indicates severe poisoning, consistent with the patient\u0027s unconscious state.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Carbon monoxide has 250-fold greater affinity for haemoglobin than oxygen, forming carboxyhaemoglobin which cannot transport oxygen.","Carbon monoxide poisoning causes tissue hypoxia despite normal arterial oxygen tension and pulse oximetry readings.","Carbon monoxide also binds to myoglobin and cytochrome c oxidase, further impairing oxygen utilisation at the cellular level.","The left shift in the oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve in carbon monoxide poisoning impairs oxygen delivery to tissues."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 9; page 408-410."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78410"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20692"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78410"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-28T18:41:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-28T18:43:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13568"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions"